      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if i switch to a generator, i should be able to stop the memory from spiking like that? also, i've been hearing people talk about \"memory leaks\" and how they can slowly eat up all the available RAM over time. is that basically what happens when a script is poorly optimized, or is that caused by something else entirely?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, switching to a generator should effectively prevent the massive, sudden spikes in memory usage you're experiencing. A memory leak, however, is a slightly different, insidious problem where memory is allocated but never properly released back to the operating system. It usually happens when references to objects are unintentionally kept alive longer than needed, causing RAM to slowly accumulate until the system runs out. It's a common symptom of poorly managed state or object lifecycles in complex code.",
      "source": "target",
